  <p><strong>Scaling Solutions:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>For small groups (1-2):</strong> Consider using a cazuela (clay pot) instead of paellera, creating arroz al horno rather than traditional paella. Alternatively, make the full recipe and enjoy leftovers—Spanish rice reheats well.</li>
    <li><strong>For large groups (8+):</strong> Multiple pans are preferable to one enormous pan. Two 46cm pans cook more evenly than one 70cm pan, and provide the psychological benefit of seconds.</li>
    <li><strong>Adjust liquid ratios:</strong> Very large pans may have different evaporation rates. For pans over 50cm, increase liquid by 10% to compensate for increased surface evaporation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Problem: Sourcing Authentic Ingredients</h3>

  <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Bomba rice, ñora peppers, vaquetas, and other authentic ingredients unavailable locally.</p>

  <p><strong>Solutions by Ingredient:</strong></p>

  <p><strong>Bomba Rice:</strong> Increasingly available at specialty food stores and online. Acceptable substitutes include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Carnaroli rice (Italian) — closest absorption characteristics</li>
    <li>Calrose rice (US) — acceptable texture but less absorption</li>
    <li>Standard short-grain — use 20% less liquid</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Ñora Peppers:</strong> Dried Spanish peppers can be ordered online. Substitutions:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Ancho chiles (Mexican) — similar sweetness, different smokiness</li>
    <li>Sun-dried tomatoes + smoked paprika — different but flavorful</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Vaquetas (Land Snails):</strong> Nearly impossible to source fresh outside Valencia. Options:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Canned escargots (French) — rinse well, flavor differs</li>
    <li>Substitute mushrooms (shiitake or porcini) — different but traditional in some variations</li>
    <li>Simply omit — many modern Valencians skip snails</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Spanish Olive Oil:</strong> Widely available, but ensure you're buying authentic Spanish (not Italian repackaged). Look for:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>D.O. designations (Sierra de Segura, Priego de Córdoba, etc.)</li>
    <li>Spanish labeling (Aceite de Oliva Virgen Extra)</li>
    <li>Harvest date, not just "best by"</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Problem: Cooking Without Proper Equipment</h3>

  <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> No paellera, no outdoor burner, no wood fire—can Spanish rice still be made?</p>

  <p><strong>Solutions:</strong></p>

  <p><strong>Without a Paellera:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Carbon steel skillet:</strong> A 12-14 inch well-seasoned carbon steel pan approximates paellera performance. Avoid non-stick (can't develop socarrat) or cast iron (too heavy, heats differently).</li>
    <li><strong>Cazuela (clay pot):</strong> Make arroz al horno instead—baked rice doesn't require paellera.</li>
    <li><strong>Large stainless sauté pan:</strong> Acceptable but suboptimal; focus on stovetop rather than oven finishing.</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Without Outdoor Burner:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Stovetop:</strong> Most paelleras up to 40cm fit across two burners. Rotate the pan frequently to distribute heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Oven finishing:</strong> Start on stovetop, finish in a 200°C (390°F) oven for the final 10 minutes. Sacrifices socarrat but produces good rice.</li>
    <li><strong>Induction paella burners:</strong> Portable units suitable for balconies or well-ventilated areas.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Problem: Cooking at Altitude</h3>

  <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Water boils at lower temperatures at altitude, affecting cooking times and liquid requirements.</p>

  <p><strong>Solutions:</strong></p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Increase liquid:</strong> At 1000m (3300ft), add 10% more liquid; at 2000m (6600ft), add 20%.</li>
    <li><strong>Extend cooking time:</strong> Expect 3-5 minutes additional cooking time per 1000m elevation.</li>
    <li><strong>Use a pressure cooker (for non-paella):</strong> Arroz caldoso and similar preparations work well in pressure cookers at altitude. Not suitable for socarrat-focused dishes.</li>
    <li><strong>Accept modified results:</strong> True socarrat is nearly impossible above 1500m (5000ft) due to reduced boiling point. Focus on flavor rather than crust formation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Preventive Best Practices</h3>

  <p>Avoiding problems is easier than fixing them:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Mise en place:</strong> Have all ingredients measured, chopped, and organized before beginning. Spanish rice cooking moves quickly once started.</li>
    <li><strong>Hot stock:</strong> Always add hot liquid to rice. Cold stock shocks the rice, disrupts cooking temperature, and extends cooking time unpredictably.</li>
    <li><strong>Consistent heat source:</strong> Whether gas, wood, or electric, understand your heat source's characteristics before cooking for guests.</li>
    <li><strong>Practice runs:</strong> Never cook a new recipe for important occasions. Make test batches to understand your equipment and ingredient behavior.</li>
    <li><strong>Quality ingredients:</strong> Spanish rice has few ingredients—each must be excellent. Poor olive oil or stale rice cannot be hidden.</li>
  </ul>

